# How does the Linux kernel handle Samsung SSD queued TRIM (FPDMA QUEUED) commands in the libata/SATA subsystem? I need to understand the code path for SEND FPDMA QUEUED command handling and where device-specific quirks for disabling queued TRIM are defined, particularly for Samsung 860 EVO drives.

Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me create a comprehensive answer about the Linux kernel's handling of Samsung SSD queued TRIM commands.

## Linux Kernel Handling of Samsung SSD Queued TRIM (FPDMA QUEUED) Commands

The Linux kernel handles queued TRIM commands for Samsung SSDs through the libata/SATA subsystem with device-specific quirks that disable this feature due to known issues. Here's the complete code path:

### 1. Device Quirks Definition

Samsung 860 EVO drives (and other Samsung SSDs) are blacklisted for queued TRIM in [drivers/ata/libata-core.c](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/drivers/ata/libata-core.c?L4271-L4274):

```c
{ "Samsung SSD 860*",		NULL,	ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM |
					ATA_QUIRK_ZERO_AFTER_TRIM |
					ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_ON_ATI |
					ATA_QUIRK_NO_LPM_ON_ATI },
```

The `ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM` flag is defined in [include/linux/libata.h](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/include/linux/libata.h?L71-L112):

```c
__ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM,	/* Do not use queued TRIM */
...
ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM		= (1U << __ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM),
```

Other affected Samsung models include:
- Samsung SSD 840* (lines 4267-4268)
- Samsung SSD 840 EVO* (lines 4264-4266)
- Samsung SSD 850* (lines 4269-4270)
- Samsung SSD 870* (lines 4275-4278)

### 2. Quirk Application During Device Configuration

When a device is configured, quirks are applied in [`ata_dev_configure()`](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/drivers/ata/libata-core.c?L2926-L2927):

```c
/* Set quirks */
dev->quirks |= ata_dev_quirks(dev);
```

The [`ata_dev_quirks()`](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/drivers/ata/libata-core.c?L4351-L4370) function matches device model numbers using glob patterns and returns the appropriate quirk flags.

### 3. NCQ Send/Recv Configuration (Where Queued TRIM is Disabled)

During NCQ capability configuration, the kernel checks for queued TRIM support via [`ata_dev_config_ncq_send_recv()`](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/drivers/ata/libata-core.c?L2276-L2298):

```c
static void ata_dev_config_ncq_send_recv(struct ata_device *dev)
{
	unsigned int err_mask;

	if (!ata_log_supported(dev, ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV)) {
		ata_dev_warn(dev, "NCQ Send/Recv Log not supported\n");
		return;
	}
	err_mask = ata_read_log_page(dev, ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV,
				     0, dev->sector_buf, 1);
	if (!err_mask) {
		u8 *cmds = dev->ncq_send_recv_cmds;

		dev->flags |= ATA_DFLAG_NCQ_SEND_RECV;
		memcpy(cmds, dev->sector_buf, ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_SIZE);

		if (dev->quirks & ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM) {
			ata_dev_dbg(dev, "disabling queued TRIM support\n");
			cmds[ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_DSM_OFFSET] &=
				~ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_DSM_TRIM;
		}
	}
}
```

**Key point**: The quirk clears the `ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_DSM_TRIM` bit from the NCQ Send/Recv capabilities, effectively disabling queued TRIM support.

### 4. TRIM Command Translation

When a SCSI UNMAP/TRIM request arrives, it's translated to ATA commands in [`ata_scsi_write_same_xlat()`](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/drivers/ata/libata-scsi.c?L3424-L3441):

```c
if (ata_ncq_enabled(dev) && ata_fpdma_dsm_supported(dev)) {
	/* Newer devices support queued TRIM commands */
	tf->protocol = ATA_PROT_NCQ;
	tf->command = ATA_CMD_FPDMA_SEND;
	tf->hob_nsect = ATA_SUBCMD_FPDMA_SEND_DSM & 0x1f;
	tf->nsect = qc->hw_tag << 3;
	tf->hob_feature = (size / 512) >> 8;
	tf->feature = size / 512;

	tf->auxiliary = 1;
} else {
	tf->protocol = ATA_PROT_DMA;
	tf->hob_feature = 0;
	tf->feature = ATA_DSM_TRIM;
	tf->hob_nsect = (size / 512) >> 8;
	tf->nsect = size / 512;
	tf->command = ATA_CMD_DSM;
}
```

### 5. Queued TRIM Support Detection

The [`ata_fpdma_dsm_supported()`](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/include/linux/libata.h?L1821-L1826) function checks if queued TRIM is available:

```c
static inline bool ata_fpdma_dsm_supported(struct ata_device *dev)
{
	return (dev->flags & ATA_DFLAG_NCQ_SEND_RECV) &&
		(dev->ncq_send_recv_cmds[ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_DSM_OFFSET] &
		 ATA_LOG_NCQ_SEND_RECV_DSM_TRIM);
}
```

For Samsung 860 EVO drives with the `ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM` quirk, this returns `false`, forcing the use of non-queued TRIM.

### 6. FPDMA SEND Command Details

The command constants are defined in [include/linux/ata.h](https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/r/github.com/torvalds/linux/-/blob/include/linux/ata.h?L234-L303):

```c
ATA_CMD_FPDMA_SEND	= 0x64,
...
/* Subcmds for ATA_CMD_FPDMA_SEND */
ATA_SUBCMD_FPDMA_SEND_DSM = 0x00,
```

### Summary of Code Path

1. **Device detection** → `ata_dev_configure()` applies quirks
2. **NCQ configuration** → `ata_dev_config_ncq_send_recv()` clears TRIM bit if `ATA_QUIRK_NO_NCQ_TRIM` is set
3. **TRIM request** → `ata_scsi_write_same_xlat()` checks `ata_fpdma_dsm_supported()`
4. **For Samsung 860 EVO**: Falls back to non-queued `ATA_CMD_DSM` (0x06) instead of `ATA_CMD_FPDMA_SEND` (0x64)

This design prevents data corruption issues that were observed with queued TRIM on Samsung SSDs, while still allowing unqueued TRIM operations to function normally.

